  "doc_id": "25154",
  "text": "The role of monoamine signaling in brain development has been firmly established. During the embryonic and early postnatal period, monoamines act as trophic factors, modulating neurodevelopmental processes, such as cell division, migration and differentiation. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] In mice, genetic maoa ablation increases brain tissue concentrations of 5-HT, NE and DA during development and early adulthood. [CITATION_4] The most prominent teratogenic consequence of murine maoa ablation, the disruption of barrel fields in the somatosensory cortex, has been linked to increased 5-HT signaling during perinatal development.",
